00:27:40.210 --> 00:27:42.370
But I think by and large, I'm
just writing about what it is

00:27:42.370 --> 00:27:44.950
that makes me anxious or angry.

00:27:44.950 --> 00:27:52.240
And trying to understand that
anger and that confusion, yeah.

00:27:52.240 --> 00:27:54.590
Yes?

00:27:54.590 --> 00:27:56.990
&gt;&gt; Do you have a favorite
place to write,

00:27:56.990 --> 00:27:59.420 position:56%
or favorite like music to listen to?

00:27:59.420 --> 00:28:00.720
&gt;&gt; M.T. ANDERSON: A favorite what?

00:28:00.720 --> 00:28:02.050
&gt;&gt; A favorite place to write?

00:28:02.050 --> 00:28:03.350
Oh, okay.

00:28:03.350 --> 00:28:04.650
&gt;&gt; M.T. ANDERSON: Yeah.

00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:06.340
&gt;&gt; Do you have a favorite place
to write, or like type of music

00:28:06.340 --> 00:28:08.810
to listen to where
you get most inspired?

00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:10.110
&gt;&gt; M.T. ANDERSON: Absolutely.

00:28:10.110 --> 00:28:11.410
Well, both things are true.

00:28:11.410 --> 00:28:14.640
So, I mean, I have an office
in my house and that's one

00:28:14.640 --> 00:28:16.630
of the best things about
being a writer, right?

00:28:16.630 --> 00:28:20.700
I mean I live in New England and
so there is snow all the time,

00:28:20.700 --> 00:28:23.730
and so I look out the window and
other people have to commute.

00:28:23.730 --> 00:28:25.840
And I'm like oh yeah,
I have to commute too

00:28:25.840 --> 00:28:28.630
from my bedroom, down the hall.

00:28:28.630 --> 00:28:31.450
It's a great gig.

00:28:31.450 --> 00:28:35.640
So, yeah, I mean as far as
listening to music while I write.

00:28:35.640 --> 00:28:38.420
I mean I listen to music
very intensely before I write

00:28:38.420 --> 00:28:41.830 position:56%
to get myself into the mood for the
specific scene that I'm going to do.

00:28:41.830 --> 00:28:44.160
But I can't listen to
music while I'm writing,

00:28:44.160 --> 00:28:48.570
because otherwise I attribute to my
own powers the power of that music.

00:28:48.570 --> 00:28:49.870
I'm writing away.

00:28:49.870 --> 00:28:53.100
I'm like, oh, man this is so
beautiful man, oh this is genius,

00:28:53.100 --> 00:28:55.960
and then I read it the next
day and it's totally boring.

00:28:55.960 --> 00:28:59.670
And it's because I was moved by
the music, not by my own writing,

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:01.980
you know, so I have to be careful

00:29:01.980 --> 00:29:06.010
of using music itself
while I'm writing, yeah.

00:29:06.010 --> 00:29:07.310
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:09.670
&gt;&gt; M.T. ANDERSON: Yeah.

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:10.970
Yes?

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:14.510
&gt;&gt; What's the weirdest thing
that's ever happened to you?

00:29:14.510 --> 00:29:18.290
[ Laughter ]

00:29:18.290 --> 00:29:19.590
&gt;&gt; M.T. ANDERSON: Pardon me?

00:29:19.590 --> 00:29:20.890
&gt;&gt; In Delaware?

00:29:20.890 --> 00:29:22.190
&gt;&gt; M.T. ANDERSON: In Delaware.

00:29:22.190 --> 00:29:23.490
Yeah, when I was, yeah.

00:29:23.490 --> 00:29:26.260
That's one of the, I've
only been shot at twice

00:29:26.260 --> 00:29:29.840
and that was the worst of the two.

00:29:29.840 --> 00:29:33.050
But the weirdest thing?

00:29:33.050 --> 00:29:34.350
Well, I'll tell you one neat thing

00:29:34.350 --> 00:29:37.060
that just recently happened
which was pretty weird.

00:29:37.060 --> 00:29:41.030
So, I recently purchased a haunted
house in the State of Vermont.

00:29:41.030 --> 00:29:44.230
They said, it's super
rural there and they're

00:29:44.230 --> 00:29:46.170
like well it's really,
really remote.

00:29:46.170 --> 00:29:50.020
And extremely cheap because
no one wants to live there,

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:52.220
but it's this 18th century house.

00:29:52.220 --> 00:29:55.860
And I was like yeah, what
could possibly go wrong?

00:29:55.860 --> 00:30:00.620
So, I moved in and I had heard
that there was an unearthly wailing

00:30:00.620 --> 00:30:04.470
that actually happened outside
of one of the upstairs windows.

00:30:04.470 --> 00:30:06.210
A child wails in the night.

00:30:06.210 --> 00:30:08.000
I'm not a believer
in ghosts by the way.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:13.000 position:56%
So, when I, about four days after I
moved in, I was sitting there typing

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:17.020
at around 9:30, and indeed I
heard a totally unearthly wailing

00:30:17.020 --> 00:30:19.070
that sounded totally human.

00:30:19.070 --> 00:30:22.040
And in fact, I thought it was
someone playing a prank on me.

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:23.340
But it was not.

00:30:23.340 --> 00:30:26.810
I'm assuming that it was
some kind of a large mammal.

00:30:26.810 --> 00:30:28.330
There are a lot of
them around there.

00:30:28.330 --> 00:30:29.630
But I still don't know.

00:30:29.630 --> 00:30:31.560
But here's the neat thing,
this is what actually moves it

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:33.160
into the realm of the kind of cool.

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:35.860
I was pulling up the floor
boards to replace them

00:30:35.860 --> 00:30:42.100 position:56%
in the upstairs bedrooms and I found
some letters from the kids who lived

00:30:42.100 --> 00:30:45.470
in that house in the 1970s,
who had put these letters

00:30:45.470 --> 00:30:47.970
in between the floor
boards to the ghosts.

00:30:47.970 --> 00:30:50.460 position:56%
And what they said, this is so cool.

00:30:50.460 --> 00:30:55.210
What they said was,
"Dear Ghost, I love you.

00:30:55.210 --> 00:30:58.030
I think you are cute.

00:30:58.030 --> 00:31:02.490
I hope your mom buys you a
corgi so you can ride on it.

00:31:02.490 --> 00:31:04.530
Do you ice skate?"

00:31:04.530 --> 00:31:07.910
Which I though was a great
thing to say to a ghost.

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:12.160
So, what is so beautiful to me as
a novelist about that is the fact

00:31:12.160 --> 00:31:17.880
that at once, the girl writing
this wants to comfort the ghost

00:31:17.880 --> 00:31:20.230
in some way, which I
think is very beautiful.

00:31:20.230 --> 00:31:24.330 position:56%
And at the same time, what she's
doing is comforting herself in a way

00:31:24.330 --> 00:31:26.780
by creating a ghost who is sweet

00:31:26.780 --> 00:31:29.110
and can be comforted,
if you see what I mean.

00:31:29.110 --> 00:31:30.770
So, it's kind of neat to see that.

00:31:30.770 --> 00:31:37.660
And also, to finish I guess, in
this image of how the legendary,

00:31:37.660 --> 00:31:40.890
or miraculous, or mythical
transforms the real.

00:31:40.890 --> 00:31:44.540
Also under those floor boards,
I found all of these items

00:31:44.540 --> 00:31:46.080
that the boy who'd
lived in the house

00:31:46.080 --> 00:31:49.070
in the seventies had
dropped in there or whatever.

00:31:49.070 --> 00:31:50.370
So, you know.

00:31:50.370 --> 00:31:52.660
Like and the whole history
of his childhood was there.

00:31:52.660 --> 00:31:56.080
So, I found the like Go Fish
cards from when he was eight.

00:31:56.080 --> 00:31:59.850
I found the baseball
cards from when he was 10.

00:31:59.850 --> 00:32:02.900
I found the Beatles record
from when he was like 12.

00:32:02.900 --> 00:32:05.750
And then I found his porn
stash when he was 15.

00:32:05.750 --> 00:32:08.890
Which funnily enough it
actually slid down next

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:13.640
to the giant central fireplace
and was a total like fire hazard.

00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:16.160
So, I was like, you know, we are;

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:18.260
they are so lucky this house
didn't burst into flame.

00:32:18.260 --> 00:32:20.470
And in a way, it would be
symbolically appropriate

00:32:20.470 --> 00:32:24.160
to have this old like Puritan
house burst into flames

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:26.460
as a result of hidden lust.

00:32:27.710 --> 00:32:32.360
So, in this kind of case,
you can see that all

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:36.670
around us there are
stories waiting to be told.

00:32:36.670 --> 00:32:40.630
And all we have to do is
look for them and understand

00:32:40.630 --> 00:32:44.050
that even the myths about
a place really resonate

00:32:44.050 --> 00:32:47.830
with that place's history
and where it actually is.

00:32:47.830 --> 00:32:49.660
What the place actually feels like.

00:32:49.660 --> 00:32:53.660
So, once again, my challenge to
all of you are to find the stories

00:32:53.660 --> 00:32:56.800
that are around you and to tell
them, because all of us want

00:32:56.800 --> 00:32:59.200
to hear what you have to say.

00:32:59.200 --> 00:33:01.000
Thank you very much.

